energy eigenstates that cannot

00:00:05.610 --> 00:00:08.070
be normalized.

00:00:08.070 --> 00:00:14.550
And when you say this
cannot be normalized,

00:00:14.550 --> 00:00:16.040
so what's the use of them?

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:19.650
They don't represent particles.

00:00:19.650 --> 00:00:23.560
Well, it's like
they e to the ipx

00:00:23.560 --> 00:00:28.470
over h bar, those
infinite plane waves.

00:00:28.470 --> 00:00:31.140
Each one by itself
cannot be normalized,

00:00:31.140 --> 00:00:34.320
but you can conserve wave
packets that are normalized.

00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:39.570
So the whole intuition that
you get with scattering states

00:00:39.570 --> 00:00:41.790
is based on the idea that
we're going to construct

00:00:41.790 --> 00:00:43.710
energy eigenstates.

00:00:43.710 --> 00:00:49.670
This time we cannot think of
them as states of a particle.

00:00:49.670 --> 00:00:50.910
Bound states, yes.

00:00:50.910 --> 00:00:53.580
We can think of them,
they're normalizable.

00:00:53.580 --> 00:00:59.010
But this energy eigenstates
and bounded scattering states

00:00:59.010 --> 00:01:01.570
are not states of one particle.

00:01:01.570 --> 00:01:07.230
So we definitely have to go
back and produce wave packets.

00:01:07.230 --> 00:01:11.160
But the intuition from
those energy eigenstates

00:01:11.160 --> 00:01:12.780
is very valuable.

00:01:12.780 --> 00:01:14.515
So scattering states.

00:01:17.650 --> 00:01:20.080
And we call them sometimes
scattering states

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:24.100
because they look like
the process of scattering.

00:01:24.100 --> 00:01:33.450
This will be non-normalizable
energy eigenstates.

00:01:39.370 --> 00:01:41.560
And you've played a
little with some of them.

00:01:41.560 --> 00:01:44.690
And we'll now study
one case in detail.

